04830nam a22006135i 9780520974708DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20202020cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209747087 a10.1525/97805209747082doi  a(DE-B1597)551607  a(OCoLC)1229161000  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aML1700b.E57 2020eb 7aMUS0280002bisacsh04a782.12231 aEnglund, Axel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDeviant Opera :bSex, Power, and Perversion on Stage /cAxel Englund. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (280 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface -- tIntroduction. Staging Deviance -- t1. Opera and Sadomasochism -- t2. Sex in Excess: Rinaldo, Alcina, and the Contemporary Baroque -- t3. Schools of Libertinage: Don Giovanni with Sade -- t4. In-House Allegories: Enactment and Actuality in Parsifal and Tosca -- t5. More or Less Human: Wozzeck, Lulu, and the Soprano Conductor -- tEpilogue. The Actuality Effect and Opera’s Quest for Authenticity -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe first book to use subversive sexuality as a lens through which to provocatively view opera in the 21st century. Imagine Armida, Handel’s Saracen sorceress, performing her breakneck coloraturas in a black figure-hugging rubber dress, beating her insubordinate furies into submission with a cane, suspending a captive Rinaldo in chains from the ceiling of her dungeon. Mozart’s peasant girl Zerlina, meanwhile, is tying up and blindfolding her fiancé to seduce him out of his jealousy of Don Giovanni. And how about Wagner’s wizard, Klingsor, ensnaring his choir of flower maidens in elaborate Japanese rope bondage? Opera, it would appear, has developed a taste for sadomasochism. For decades now, radical stage directors have repeatedly dressed canonical operas—from Handel and Mozart to Wagner and Puccini, and beyond—in whips, chains, leather, and other regalia of SM and fetishism. Deviant Opera seeks to understand this phenomenon, approaching the contemporary visual code of perversion as a lens through which opera focuses and scrutinizes its own configurations of sex, gender, power, and violence. The emerging image is that of an art form that habitually plays with an eroticization of cruelty and humiliation, inviting its devotees to take sensual pleasure in the suffering of others. Ultimately, Deviant Opera argues that this species of opera fantasizes about breaking the boundaries of its own role-playing, and pushing its erotic power exchanges from the enacted to the actual.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aOperaxProduction and directionxHistory. 0aSex in opera. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Opera.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020 Englishz978311070474708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020z9783110704532oZDB-23-DKU08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069041540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520974708?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520974708423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520974708/original  a978-3-11-069041-5  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-